# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# FsiX is the **F# Interactive (fsi) REPL extension**
# by soweli-p — wraps `fsi.exe` with project/solution
# loading, daemon mode (JSON-RPC server), and library
# search path management.  Pivots from Swift
# ArgumentParser (R283 yap) into the **F# language
# tooling cluster**.  Sister to other .NET CLIs
# (dotnet, fsi, paket).  **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's
# **first documented F# Argu CLI** — adds F# to the
# cross-language CLI taxonomy (23 library variants
# now).
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **F#'s `Argu`**
# library at `open Argu` — corpus's **first documented
# F# Argu CLI**.  Argu is **the** standard F# CLI
# library — uses F#'s **discriminated unions** to
# model the CLI surface as a TYPE.  Used by FAKE
# (F# build tool), Paket (F# package manager),
# fsprojects/* (F# Foundation projects), and most F#
# tooling.  Extends the **cross-language CLI taxonomy**
# to TWENTY-THREE library variants: Rust (6), Go (4),
# Python (3), Crystal OptionParser (R269), Haskell
# optparse-applicative (R270), OCaml Cmdliner (R271),
# C POSIX getopt (R272), Java picocli (R276), Kotlin
# clikt (R277), Scala decline (R278), Dart args
# (R279), Ruby OptionParser (R280), Perl Getopt::Long
# (R281), PHP Symfony Console (R282), Swift
# ArgumentParser (R283), **F# Argu** (R284 — NEW).
# **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 23 cross-language CLI
# library variants documented.  Documents the
# **F# discriminated-union-based CLI pattern**:
# ```fsharp
#   type Arguments =
#     | Sln of fileName: string
#     | [<Unique>] Dir of workingDirectory: string
#     | [<Alt("-r"); Sep(":")>] Reference of assembly: string
#     | [<Last>] Other of args: string list
#     interface IArgParserTemplate with
#       member s.Usage =
#         match s with
#         | Sln _ -> "loads sources for solution"
#         | Dir _ -> "alternative working directory"
#         | ...
# ```
# Distinct from Rust clap derive's enum variants
# (R247+ sncast) — both use sum-types but F#'s
# discriminated unions allow ARBITRARY TUPLE TYPES
# in each case (e.g. `host: string * port: int` for
# a 2-tuple flag) while Rust enum variants need
# struct or tuple-struct forms.  F#'s approach is
# MORE FLEXIBLE for representing flag-value structures.
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **F# attributes
# on DU cases via `[<Attribute>]` syntax** at
# Args.fs:15-21 — Argu's declarative attributes
# annotate each DU case to control parsing behavior:
#   `[<Unique>]` — flag can only appear ONCE on the
#                  CLI (e.g. `--dir foo` works; `--dir
#                  foo --dir bar` errors)
#   `[<Alt("-r")>]` — alternative shorter CLI name
#                     (e.g. `Reference` can also be
#                     invoked as `-r`)
#   `[<Sep(":")>]` — value list separator (e.g.
#                    `--reference a:b:c` parses as
#                    list ["a"; "b"; "c"])
#   `[<Last>]`     — must be the LAST positional;
#                    captures trailing args after `--`
# Plus attributes can be COMBINED with `;`:
# `[<Alt("-r"); Sep(":")>] Reference of ...`.
# Documents the **F# attribute-based CLI metadata**
# pattern — distinct from Java picocli's annotations
# (R276) and Swift ArgumentParser's property wrappers
# (R283 yap) in surface syntax but conceptually
# similar.  F#'s attributes are CASE-LEVEL (annotate
# DU cases) while picocli's annotations are FIELD-
# LEVEL.  Corpus's **first documented F# attribute-
# on-DU-case CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **`type Sep =
# CustomAssignmentOrSpacedAttribute`** and **`type
# Alt = AltCommandLineAttribute`** at Args.fs:5-6 —
# F#'s TYPE ALIAS feature to RENAME Argu attributes
# for brevity.  Without these aliases, the code would
# read `[<CustomAssignmentOrSpacedAttribute(":")>]
# Reference of ...` which is verbose.  Documents the
# **type alias for attribute renaming** F# idiom —
# unique to F# (and other ML-family languages).
# Distinct from Rust's lack of attribute aliasing
# (you'd write `#[clap(...)]` always with the full
# name).  Corpus's first documented type-alias-for-
# attribute-shortening.
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **TUPLE-TYPED
# flag values** at Args.fs:16 — `Daemon of host:
# string * port: int` declares a flag that takes
# **TWO VALUES**: a host string AND an integer port.
# F#'s tuple types are first-class in DUs; Argu
# auto-parses 2 consecutive CLI tokens into a tuple.
# User invocation: `fsix --daemon localhost 8080`.
# Documents the **tuple-typed multi-value flag
# pattern** — distinct from clap derive's separate
# fields per value (R249 cairo-profiler uses two
# separate fields for host + port), Click's two
# separate `--host` and `--port` options (R266
# uvicorn), and picocli's `arity = 2` attribute (R276
# checkstyle).  F#'s approach is the MOST CONCISE
# for multi-value flags.  Corpus's **first documented
# tuple-typed flag values**.
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **LIST-TYPED
# flag values** at Args.fs:20 — `Lib of folderList:
# string list` declares a flag taking a LIST of
# directories.  Argu collects multiple CLI tokens
# into the F# list.  Plus the `[<Alt("-l")>]`
# attribute provides a short alias.  Distinct from
# tuple-typed (fixed N values) — list-typed accepts
# ANY NUMBER of values.  Documents the **list-typed
# variadic flag** pattern — similar to clap derive's
# `Vec<String>` field type (R260 dua) but expressed
# via F#'s native list type.
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **`interface
# IArgParserTemplate` with declarative `member s
# .Usage` pattern-match** at Args.fs:23-32 —
# implementing Argu's IArgParserTemplate interface on
# the Arguments DU type provides help text per case:
# ```fsharp
#   interface IArgParserTemplate with
#     member s.Usage =
#       match s with
#       | Sln _ -> "loads sources for solution"
#       | Dir _ -> "alternative working directory"
#       | ...
# ```
# Documents the **interface-implementation help-text
# pattern** in F# Argu — uses F#'s native pattern-
# matching on the DU case to produce help text.
# Plus the `s` parameter is the DU value itself, with
# `_` discards for the case's payload (we only need
# the case discriminator for help text).  Distinct
# from clap derive's `#[doc = "..."]` doc-comment-
# as-help (R247+) and Click's `help="..."` keyword
# arg (R266 uvicorn).  F#'s approach uses LANGUAGE
# FEATURES (pattern matching, interfaces) rather than
# library-specific metadata.  Corpus's **first
# documented IArgParserTemplate interface pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: FsiX uses **`[<Last>]`
# attribute for trailing args after `--`** at
# Args.fs:21 — `[<Last>] Other of args: string list`
# captures all CLI tokens after the special `--`
# separator into a `string list`.  These are
# forwarded to fsi.exe.  Documents the **trailing-
# args-after-double-dash pattern** in Argu —
# convergent with R258 bevy's clap `last = true,
# name = "ARGS"` (R258) and Click's `nargs=-1`
# (R266).  Plus R263 lazygit uses flaggy's positional
# `AddPositionalValue` with `required: false`.
# F#'s `[<Last>]` attribute is the most TERSE form.
# Used heavily in REPL wrappers (FsiX wraps fsi.exe)
# and shell-like tools.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 9 flags decoded source-direct from Arguments DU at
# Args.fs lines 13-22.
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help (Argu auto-adds)]' \
  '*--sln=[load all sources and dependencies for given solution]:file:_files -g "*.sln"' \
  '*--proj=[load all sources and dependencies for given fsproj file]:file:_files -g "*.fsproj"' \
  '--dir=[alternative working directory (Unique attribute)]:dir:_files -/' \
  '--daemon=[start daemon listening for JSON-RPC requests (Unique; tuple host * port; 2 values)]:host\ port:' \
  '*'{-r+,--reference=}'[make F#/.NET assembly available (Alt; Sep colon-separated)]:assembly:_files' \
  '*--load=[compile source at startup + load constructs (Sep colon-separated)]:file:_files -g "*.fs(x|i|)"' \
  '*--use=[use file on startup as initial input (Sep colon-separated)]:file:_files -g "*.fs(x|i|)"' \
  '*'{-l+,--lib=}'[directory to search for referenced assemblies (Alt; list-typed)]:dir:_files -/' \
  '*::trailing args to fsi.exe (Last attribute; after --):_files'
